<br>
Terrellion scratched his chin, thoughtfully.  “Um…  We open the doors and go in?”<br>
<br>
“Brilliant Terr…  Now, how do we do that?”<br>
<br>
“You’re the wood elf.  Push em open.”<br>
<br>
Ayslyn contemplated the pair of thirty-foot high doors dubiously.  “I could try, but I doubt even I could budge them.  Alec, you got any ideas?”<br>
<br>
The mage looked up from his book.  “Yeah, I think I might be able to help you open the doors.”  He mouthed a few words from his book, memorizing the spell, and nodded briskly.  “Alright, I’m ready.  Go ahead Ays.”<br>
<br>
Ayslyn nodded and unstrung his bow.  He wrapped the string carefully around it and slid it into his enchanted quiver.  Rolling his shoulders to loosen the muscles, he cracked his knuckles and took up position in front of the door.  Behind him, he heard Alec begin to chant.  Leaning forward slightly, he put his shoulder and hand against the door and pushed.  His trailing foot slid a little in the dirt before finding purchase.  Tight, corded muscles in his arms, back and legs contracted as Ayslyn brought all of his considerable strength to bear on the door.  Alec finished the spell and thrust his hand out in front of him, palm out.  A glowing hand taller than Ayslyn himself appeared above the ranger.  Slowly the door began to groan and creak as ancient hinges were forced into use.  The door swung open slowly.  Ayslyn shifted his weight, and began to step forward, step after step, forcing the door open.  The muscles in Ayslyn’s shoulders and legs began to burn with the strain.  He tightened his focus, ignoring everything but taking step after agonizing step.  The sudden touch of someone’s hand on his back shocked him.  Spinning, he almost lost his balance as the ignored strain on his body demanded strict attention.  He leaned heavily on the now open door, and slid carefully down to the ground, panting.  <br>
<br>
Alec handed him a flask.  “Drink this.  Esme left us a few potions for while she was away.  Seems she knew we wouldn’t wait for her to get back before heading out.”<br>
<br>
Ayslyn nodded, exhausted and drank down the contents of the flask.  Honey sweet, he swallowed the potion and smiled as it’s healing warmth flowed over him, washing away the tension, and exhaustion.  He stood, and made his way to his horse. Withdrawing a linen cloth from his saddle pack, he wiped the sweat from his face and arms.  “Those things could come in handy,” he remarked to the other two, as they prepared to enter the tomb.  He took his bow from the quiver and strung it, pulling back the string lightly to test the pull.  Nodding in satisfaction, he turned to the two they had hired to drive the wagon, and watch their horses while they explored the tomb.  He took a small bag from his packs and handed it over to them.  “Make sure to give Midnight a couple of apples.” He patted the horse’s neck affectionately.  Midnight whinnied and nodded.  Ayslyn chuckled and made his way to the open door of the tomb, drawing and nocking an arrow as he did.  “Alright lads, are we ready?”  His friends nodded.  “Lets head in then.”  He stepped into the darkness.<br>
