<br>
The interior of the tomb was dark.  Centuries had passed since anyone had been inside it, and why light someplace that no one living is likely to see.  Ayslyn’s eyes swiftly adapted to the darkness, and he slipped further into the tomb, ready to draw back his arrow at any sign of danger.  The hard clacking of their boots striking against the flagstones echoed down the corridor.  Ayslyn’s eyes flicked back and forth, looking for any side passages, and more importantly, any enemies.  “So,” he whispered back to his friends, “What can we expect?”<br>
<br>
Alec replied thoughtfully, “The adventuring company that is buried here consisted of a paladin, cleric, sorceress, and a pair of warriors.  They were moderately successful.  However, it doesn’t look as though the tomb has been opened before, so it should be empty.”<br>
<br>
A throat ripping, high pitched screech accompanied the wight as it charged out of a side room and swiped blackened, fouled claws at Ayslyn.  He threw himself backwards, away from the beast, pulling back the bowstring and letting fly the arrow he had nocked.  The arrow flew, straight and true, imbedding itself in the creature’s thigh.  The wight screeched in pain and glared hatefully at Ayslyn.  Terrellion stepped between them, sword and shield at the ready as Ayslyn tucked and rolled, landing sprawled against the wall, dazed.  He shook his head hard to clear it and leapt to his feet.  The Wight launched itself at Terrellion who calmly blocked it with his shield.  Hardened claws scraped at metal as Terrellion batted away the creature’s attacks.  He swung his sword up and under his shield.  Razor sharp steel met flesh as the blade sliced into the wight’s side.  He gripped his shield tight and rushed it, smashing it into the wall, and jumped back.  <br>
<br>
A keening wail from behind them tore Ayslyn’s attention from the fight before him.  A wraith had ghosted through the wall and reached for Alec.  The mage chanted softly and extended on hand.  A spread of crimson darts flew from his fingertips and struck the wraith hard.  Ayslyn drew an arrow and began firing into the creature as well.  Soon, with one final pitiful cry, it slumped to the ground.  They turned back in time to see Terrellion finish off the wight.  Ayslyn looked at Alec skeptically.  “Empty,” was all he said.<br>
<br>
Alec shrugged, “Course, I could be wrong,” he replied with a grin.  Ayslyn chuckled and motioned to the room that the two creatures had come from.  Within it, they found that the tombs of the cleric, and one of the warriors had been desecrated.  Ayslyn and Alec exchanged worried glances, but it was Terrellion that spoke up.<br>
<br>
“You don’t suppose that the two we just killed,” he pointed at the open and empty sarcophagi.<br>
<br>
Alec frowned.  “By all accounts that I could find, none of the members died at the hands of undead.  Miiria, the cleric, died in a rockslide, and Hadren, the warrior here, he died in a barfight.  There is nothing that would suggest that they would come back.”<br>
<br>
Ayslyn tapped his chin thoughtfully.  “Maybe something ate the corpses.  There might be a ghoul about.  Or perhaps a ghast.”<br>
Alec nodded.  “Either way, we’ll need to explore a bit more.  Let’s go.”<br>
<br>
They left to room, and made their way further into the tomb.  After a few minutes, they reached the end of the corridor.  A single door led off to the right.  Stepping up to it, carefully, Ayslyn took hold of the handle and opened it, and stepped into the small room.  The remains of an altar filled to opposite wall of the room, and another door stood in the left hand wall.  Ayslyn knelt to examine the wreckage.  “Look at this.” He poked at the remains.  “This isn’t time, or an accident.”  He held up a piece of the table leg, pointing to the many cuts in it.  “We’re talking about pure malice here.  Someone had a serious mad on when they did this.”<br>
<br>
Alec slowly read the name above the door.  “Moritval.  That would be the paladin.”  He looked worriedly at Ayslyn.  <br>
<br>
Ayslyn shrugged, and tested the handle to the door.  “Locked,” he said.  He looked to Alec, who shook his head.  Shrugging again, he stepped back and kicked the door, just above the handle, hard.  Ancient wood and metal tore apart under the force of the blow, and the door flew open.  They entered the long room cautiously.  A sarcophagus stood atop a three-tiered dais at the end of the room, a large chandelier hanging above it.  A suit of ancient armour stood off to the side.  Even from here, they could tell that the sarcophagus was closed.  “Looks like Moritval is still sleeping soundly,” Ayslyn said as he approached the dais.<br>
<br>
Twin pinpricks of red-hot flame burst to life within the visor of the armour.  Alec shouted a warning as it snatched up its greatsword and swung at Ayslyn.  The magic within his bracers flowed through him and Ayslyn leapt high into the air.  He caught hold of the chandelier and swore.  “A deathknight?  What the hell is going on here?”<br>
<br>
The ancient armour creaked and groaned at the deathknight moved away from the wall.  Once again, Terrellion moved forward to intercept it.  Ayslyn locked his legs around the chandelier and swung forward to hang down.  He drew an arrow from his enchanted quiver.  Terrellion and the deathknight came together with a crash.  The deathknight swung its sword wide and crashed into Terrellion’s shield, sparks flying as metal raked against metal.  Terrellion’s knees buckled under the blow, but he kept his footing, and swung hard, catching it in the leg.<br>
<br>
Ayslyn drew back his bow, and sighted down the shaft.  He called out, “Left” and let fly.  Terrellion danced to the left just in time for the arrow to sail past him and lodge itself into the elbow joint of the armour.  He fired twice more, this time hitting the shoulder joint.  Alec was chanting furiously in the doorway.  He thrust his hands forward and a virulently green missile shot away from him.  It struck the deathknight in the chest, and a green liquid splattered over the armour.  Within seconds it began to hiss and smoke as the acid began to eat away at the armour.  Meanwhile, Terrellion had continued to hack and bash at it.  A savage blow to its knee caused its leg to collapse under it, and it crashed into the wall.  Ayslyn had a sudden idea.  “Head” he called out, drawing one of his special dragon-slaying arrows.  He nocked the solid steel shaft and drew back the string.  Quickly sighting down the shaft, he let fly.  The arrow streaked across the room to strike dead on target.  The helmet of the deathknight crumpled underneath it, the knight himself, slumped to the floor.  The twin points of light within the helmet flickered and vanished.<br>
<br>
Ayslyn dropped down from the chandelier, landing in a crouch.  As he straightened, he looked at each of his companions.  “Alright.  Now, that was definitely the paladin come back as a deathknight.  Someone want to venture a guess about why all these adventurers came back as undead?”<br>
<br>
Alec shrugged helplessly, “I haven’t a clue.  A paladin returning as a deathknight is a big deal, and doesn’t just happen.  Somebody deliberately did that to him.” He pointed to the pile of armour.<br>
<br>
“Guys,” Terrellion interrupted.  “We’re still missing two.”<br>
<br>
Ayslyn looked about the room.  “And there are no more doors.  We’ve seen everything in this tomb, unless…”<br>
<br>
Alec and Terrellion nodded, agreeing.  Alec said, “Terr, you search this room, I’ll take the last one, and Ays, you check the other one.  Let’s see what we find.”<br>
