<br>
Ayslyn nodded and made his way back to the other tomb.  Slowly he made his way around the perimeter of the room, carefully checking the walls.  As he reached the back wall, his ears twitched slightly.  He heard the soft whisper of wind, and felt it on his fingertips.  Feeling his way along the wall, he soon found the gap.  He carefully traced out the outline of the hidden door, and began to search for the opening mechanism.  Smiling as he felt one of the stones shift under his gentle probing, he pushed it, and the door slid into the floor.  “I found it,” he called out.  Within moments, he two companions were beside him.  “Ready?” he asked them.  They nodded in unison.  “Right then.  Off we go.”  He made his way into a short passage and down a steep flight of stairs, an arrow nocked and ready.<br>
<br>
The stairs ended in an archway.  Beyond it was a massive room, easily two hundred feet long, and half as wide.  Torches flared to life as they entered, momentarily blinding them.  Ayslyn squinted as his eyes adjusted.  A dais dominated the far end of the room, along with the sarcophagus atop it.  “Looks like this is number four,” he quipped as they cautiously made their way down the room.<br>
<br>
As they approached the halfway point, a massive cloud burst forth in front of them.  They reeled back from the stench of brimstone and death.  The smoke cleared, revealing what looked to be a ten-foot tall bear with massive curling ram horns.  It stood on its hind legs and regarded them malevolently.  “Return from whence you came and never return,” it bellowed at them.<br>
<br>
“Sweet Rhiannon,” Alec swore, “A guardian demon.  What in the nine hells is a guardian demon doing here?”<br>
<br>
Ayslyn drew back his bowstring and fired, “Less talk!  More fight!” he called out.  Terrellion moved forward to engage the beast as Ayslyn dashed to the side to flank it.  Alec shook his head and circled round the other side.  He began chanting.  Again, a spread of crimson missiles shot from his outstretched hands, sidling around Terrellion to strike the demon.  Ayslyn fired arrow after arrow into its back and Terrellion struck it from the front with his sword.  The demon roared in pain, but they didn’t relent.  Soon it drew a single shuddering breath, and fell to the ground.  “I guess they don’t make guardian demons like they used to,” Ayslyn grinned as he returned the arrow he had just drawn to his quiver.<br>
<br>
They looked down the length of the room, watching warily.  When nothing else appeared, they continued.  They mounted the dais, and looked down upon the sarcophagus.  “Anyone care to lay odds on what he’s become?” Ayslyn grinned.<br>
<br>
Alec chuckled and dusted off the nameplate.  “Nerram.  Yup, this was the leader of the group.”  He nodded, and Ayslyn handed him his bow.<br>
<br>
“Cover me, Terr,” Ayslyn asked as he moved to get a good grip on the lid.  He pushed, hard, and the lid shifted.  He kept at it, until finally, the lid toppled over and crashed to the floor.  Within the sarcophagus, lay Nerram’s remains, bedecked in armour and jewels, and holding a longsword.  Alec passed the bow back to Ayslyn, and they watched the remains carefully.  After a few moments, Ayslyn sighed.  “Alright, I’m confused.”  He spun round, and leaned against the sarcophagus.  “Anyone care to present a theory?”  He looked back and forth at his two friends.  “No?  What about the last one?  The sorceress?  Where is she?  There doesn’t seem to be another way out of this room.  What was her name?”<br>
<br>
“Curiously enough,” Alec replied, “I don’t know.  Each of the others were listed, but all that I could find about her was that she was a member of the company, she was human, and she was a sorceress.”<br>
<br>
“Right, then.  I guess we check the walls,” Ayslyn rubbed his hands together.  They split up and began to search the walls carefully.  Terrellion even checked the floor for trap doors.  After some time, they all returned to the dais.  Ayslyn frowned.  “Not a thing.  So, now what.”<br>
<br>
Alec and Terrellion both shrugged.  “We could try the rod,” Alec said hesitantly.<br>
<br>
Terrellion frowned.  “The last time we used that, you wound up with an apprentice with a penchant for Wild magic.”  Alec winced, remembering.<br>
<br>
Ayslyn shook his head.  “No, Terr, Alec is right.  I can’t think of anything else.  But first, we take all that stuff off him.  If he’s hostile, I don’t want him to have anything to attack us with.”  They nodded, and began to strip everything off the corpse.  Ayslyn held up the helm that it had.  On one side, a gruesome, snarl toothed face glared at him, but on the other, was a peaceful, smiling face.  He shrugged and tossed it on the growing pile of junk on the floor.<br>
<br>
Alec withdrew a slender, three-foot long rod from his pack.  “Alright then, ready?”  Ayslyn nocked an arrow and nodded along with Terrellion.  Alec gently touched Nerram’s remains and spoke a single word of power.  A brilliant flash of light burst from the tip of the rod, and was absorbed into the corpse.  <br>
<br>
Slowly at first, but steadily quickening, the corpse began to reconstitute.  Cartilage formed on the bones and joints, to be covered in thick ropey muscles.  Finally, skin covered all of that.  Nerram groaned aloud and slowly sat up.  Looking about, he noticed Ayslyn and Terrellion, weapons at the ready.  “Who are you people?” he asked, confused.  “Where am I?”<br>
<br>
“Seems friendly enough, for now,” Ayslyn remarked.  <br>
<br>
“We are a company of adventurers, as you were,” Alec began.<br>
<br>
“Were?”<br>
<br>
Alec cleared his throat.  “You’ve been dead for about fifteen centuries.  We were exploring your tomb, and found the others turned into undead.  There was a demon guarding you.”<br>
<br>
“That witch!” Nerram swore.<br>
<br>
“Excuse me?” Ayslyn asked, confused.<br>
<br>
“Rose!  That witch gave me an enchanted helmet.  After that, I had no control over my actions.  I was like a rider in my own body, with someone else holding the reigns.  Oh, gods.  Miiria.  I caused a rockslide to kill her.  And her husband, Hadren.  I knifed him in the back during a bar fight.”  He buried his face in his hands and began to weep.<br>
<br>
Ayslyn looked confused.  He reached down, and retrieved the helm.  “This helmet?  ‘s pretty ugly.  Why did you wear this?”<br>
<br>
Nerram shook his head, “That wasn’t it.  I’ve never seen it before.”<br>
<br>
Ayslyn raised an eyebrow.  “You were wearing it when we found you.”<br>
<br>
Alec looked up in shock.  “Give me that,” he said, snatching the helmet away.  He sat down on the steps and began rummaging in his packs.  He withdrew a pearl, and holding it gingerly between his forefinger and his thumb, he began to chant.<br>
<br>
“What in the nine hells is he doing?” Nerram asked.  Ayslyn shrugged.<br>
<br>
After a moment, Alec stood triumphantly.  “I got it!” he exulted.  “The enchantment on this helm reverses your moral stance.  You were a force for good, so when you put this on -- I can only guess that she cast some sort of illusion on it – you turned to the forces of evil.  That is why you lost control of yourself.”<br>
<br>
Nerram swore heavily.  “If she wasn’t dead by now, I’d kill her.”<br>
<br>
“Why did you call her Rose?”  Ayslyn mused.<br>
<br>
“She had a rose tattooed on her breast.”<br>
<br>
“Good reason.”<br>
<br>
They led Nerram out of the tomb, and took him back to town with them.  They would hand him over to Miranda.  If anyone knew what it was like to wake up centuries out of their own time, she would.  Perhaps she would be able to help him adjust.<br>
