<br>
The trip to Evermeet was easy.  Many of the elven cities were connect with mystic portals.  Step into one here in Evereska, and you would step out another, leagues distant, as though you had just stepped from one room to another.  But still, it came as some surprise to Ayslyn that the portal from Evereska to Evermeet was located in the temple of Hanalli, the goddess of love and beauty.  Ayslyn stared about at a crowd of Hanalli’s priestesses.  A tall Gold Elf, long platinum hair flowing down her back, smiled at him. “Guys,” he remarked, “We’re not in that much of a hurry, are we?”<br>
<br>
Alec looked thoughtful, considering the idea.  Terrellion frowned.  “We don’t have the time.”  Ayslyn sighed, but dutifully followed his friends back to the portal, waving farewell to the lovely elven women.  <br>
<br>
As they reached the back of the temple, Ayslyn eyed the glowing archway, hidden behind the statue of Hanalli, dubiously.  “So, we step through that, and we’ll be there?” he asked, not quite convinced it could be that simple.<br>
<br>
The head priestess, whom had aged exceptionally well, even for an elf, smiled gently at him.  “Put your concerns aside good ranger.  Place your faith in the gods.”<br>
<br>
Ayslyn almost frowned, but caught himself in time.  They had, some years previous, stopped some slime god from bringing his avatar into the world in the tunnels and caverns of the Underdark, and after that incident in the Forest of Wyrms, and what Alec had done to the Zentrim, well, they seemed to be angering a number of dieties.  Ayslyn figured that they really couldn’t afford to alienate any of their own.  He smiled, obligingly, and followed Terrellion and Alec into the portal, giving the blonde priestess one last wink before he vanished.<br>
<br>
Warm sun fell on his face, and the scents of freshly tended lawns washed over him.  He looked about him wonderingly at the massive garden they had stepped into.  Carefully tended, and shaped trees lined the harmoniously ordered rows.  Delicately balanced beds of flowers artfully sprawled in rows that were rigidly arranged to look casual.  He breathed deeply, but the delicate blends of perfumes from the flowers seemed artificial to him.  Here was only sweetness and light.  None of the earthier scents that were found in true nature were to be found here.  Here, nature was tamed to their own ideal.  Silver Elves, he decided, would just never get it.<br>
<br>
He followed Alec and Terrellion down a straight path towards the exit from the garden.  A pair of guards stood attention at the vine-covered archway.  They waved Terrellion and Alec through.  Glaring at Ayslyn, they began to wave him through as well.  Ayslyn grinned, impishly, and stuck his thumbs in his belt.  Leaning back slightly, he sauntered past them.  “Afternoon boys.  How’re y’all doin’?” he drawled, allowing all of the thick Moonshae’s accent, that he had lost over the years since he had left, flow back into his speech.  The guard on the left gasped, while the other just sneered at him.  Ayslyn just grinned wider, and winked as he continued after his friends.<br>
